::code-comment{title="[P0] Auth dependency requires a JWT claim the contract never issues" body="`get_current_user` rejects tokens unless they contain `email`, but the frozen contract and session-2 prompt only require `sub`, `username`, and `exp`. If session 2 follows the contract, every protected request will fail authentication. Either stop requiring `email` here or change the contract and all token issuers together." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\server\\app\\deps.py" start=32 end=37 priority=0 confidence=0.99}
::code-comment{title="[P1] Unauthorized responses will use FastAPI's `detail` envelope instead of the contract's `error` envelope" body="This dependency raises plain `HTTPException(detail=\"unauthorized\")`, and there is no exception handler in `main.py` to translate that into `{ \"error\": \"unauthorized\" }` as required by the contract. That means every auth failure on protected routes will violate the agreed HTTP response shape and likely break client-side handling." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\server\\app\\deps.py" start=21 end=30 priority=1 confidence=0.97}

**Findings**

- `[P0]` [server/app/deps.py](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\server\app\deps.py):32 requires `email` in the JWT payload, but [BUILD_CONTRACT.md](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\BUILD_CONTRACT.md):263 and the session-2 contract only require `sub`, `username`, and `exp`. If session 2 implements the token exactly as specified, all protected HTTP endpoints will reject valid tokens.
- `[P1]` [server/app/deps.py](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\server\app\deps.py):21 raises `HTTPException(..., detail="unauthorized")`, and [server/app/main.py](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\server\app\main.py):17 has no exception handler to convert that into the contract’s `{ "error": "unauthorized" }` shape. Any auth failure will return FastAPI’s default `{"detail":"unauthorized"}` instead of the agreed envelope.

I didn’t find other concrete session-1 defects in the infra/runtime scope. The schema matches the contract, and a dry-run `pip install .` in `server/` succeeded. I did not run a full Docker build or compose startup in this review.

::code-comment{title="[P2] Invalid canvas IDs crash instead of returning a contract error" body="Both `get_canvas` and `invite_to_canvas` call `UUID(canvas_id)` before any error handling. A malformed canvas id will raise `ValueError` and return a 500 instead of the contract's 404-style error response, which makes these routes brittle to bad links or client bugs." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\server\\app\\canvas.py" start=121 end=122 priority=2 confidence=0.94}
::code-comment{title="[P0] Canvas members can update or delete shapes in other canvases" body="The persistence helpers only filter by `id`, not by both `id` and `canvas_id`. Once a user is authorized onto any canvas, a crafted op with another canvas's shape id can update or delete that shape. This breaks isolation between canvases and violates the membership boundary the WebSocket auth is supposed to enforce." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\server\\app\\ws.py" start=181 end=189 priority=0 confidence=0.98}
::code-comment{title="[P1] Realtime update path allows illegal shape type mutation" body="The contract freezes `type` after creation, but `_ALLOWED_UPDATE_COLS` excludes only `id`, so update ops can still write `type`. A malicious or buggy client can convert an existing shape into a different kind, which the frontend state model does not expect and the contract explicitly forbids." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\server\\app\\ws.py" start=161 end=174 priority=1 confidence=0.97}
::code-comment{title="[P0] Session 4 is not wired into the running app" body="The app entrypoint still renders a placeholder `<div>Whiteboard</div>`, so none of the auth flow, canvas list, invite flow, whiteboard UI, WebSocket sync, or undo/redo work is actually reachable. The supporting client files may exist, but the shipped frontend still fails the required feature set end to end." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\client\\src\\App.tsx" start=1 end=2 priority=0 confidence=0.99}
::code-comment{title="[P1] Undo can recreate a bogus placeholder shape" body="When reversing a delete without finding the original snapshot, `reverseOp` fabricates a zero-size rectangle and re-adds it. That violates the contract, which requires the pre-delete snapshot for delete undo, and it can silently corrupt board state with junk shapes instead of failing safely." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\client\\src\\operations.ts" start=28 end=46 priority=1 confidence=0.96}

**Findings**

- `[P0]` Session 3: [ws.py](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\server\app\ws.py#L181) scopes `update` and `delete` by `id` only, not `(canvas_id, id)`. Any authenticated member of one canvas can mutate a known shape id from another canvas.
- `[P0]` Session 4: [App.tsx](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\client\src\App.tsx#L1) still renders only a placeholder, so the implemented client pieces are not actually reachable in the running app.
- `[P1]` Session 3: [ws.py](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\server\app\ws.py#L161) allows `type` to be updated even though the contract makes shape type immutable after creation.
- `[P1]` Session 4: [operations.ts](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\client\src\operations.ts#L28) fabricates a placeholder rectangle when undoing a delete without a snapshot, which can corrupt board state.
- `[P2]` Session 2: [canvas.py](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\server\app\canvas.py#L121) parses `canvas_id` with `UUID(...)` without handling invalid input. A malformed canvas URL will raise 500 instead of returning a contract error. The same problem appears in the invite route at [canvas.py](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\server\app\canvas.py#L216).

**Notes**

- Session 2 otherwise looked broadly aligned with the contract, but it still inherits the auth-envelope issue already found in session 1.
- I could not complete a frontend build verification because `npm run build` fails in this checkout with `tsc` not found, which indicates client dependencies are not installed locally yet.

::code-comment{title="[P0] Client-side optimistic reconciliation ignores server ordering" body="The client applies its own op immediately, then later drops the echoed op if the `opId` matches. If another user's conflicting op arrives before that echo, this client preserves local-first ordering instead of the server's `seq` ordering and can diverge from the authoritative board state. Same-field concurrent edits are especially vulnerable here. The client needs seq-aware reconciliation or a pending-op rebase, not a blind 'skip own echo' rule." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\client\\src\\components\\CanvasPage.tsx" start=615 end=624 priority=0 confidence=0.99}
::code-comment{title="[P1] Local edits are silently dropped while the socket is not open" body="`sendOp` mutates local state and records the op as pending before attempting to send it, but `sendWs` becomes a no-op unless the socket is already `OPEN`. Any draw, move, resize, delete, or recolor performed during startup or after a disconnect appears locally but never reaches the server, so it disappears on refresh and never reaches collaborators." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\client\\src\\components\\CanvasPage.tsx" start=121 end=135 priority=1 confidence=0.98}
::code-comment{title="[P1] Initial HTTP load can overwrite newer websocket state" body="The canvas detail fetch and the websocket session run in parallel, and both overwrite `shapesRef.current`. If the GET resolves after `init` or after one or more live `op` messages, the older HTTP snapshot can clobber newer real-time state on this client. Gate the HTTP result so it only seeds state before websocket init, or make websocket init the sole source of initial board state." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\client\\src\\components\\CanvasPage.tsx" start=573 end=578 priority=1 confidence=0.97}
::code-comment{title="[P2] Malformed websocket canvas IDs are not rejected cleanly" body="The pre-accept membership query passes the raw `canvasId` string into a UUID-backed query without validating it first. An invalid canvas id can raise an asyncpg conversion error before the socket is accepted, turning a bad URL into an internal error instead of a clean auth or membership rejection." file="C:\\Users\\sahil\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\Mechanize_takehome\\server\\app\\ws.py" start=202 end=226 priority=2 confidence=0.92}

**Findings**

- `[P0]` [CanvasPage.tsx](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\client\src\components\CanvasPage.tsx#L615): client optimistic reconciliation still does not honor server-authoritative ordering. Same-field concurrent edits can leave one client with a different final value than the server and other peers.
- `[P1]` [CanvasPage.tsx](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\client\src\components\CanvasPage.tsx#L121): local edits are applied even when the websocket is disconnected, but they are never queued or retried. Those changes are lost on refresh and never broadcast.
- `[P1]` [CanvasPage.tsx](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\client\src\components\CanvasPage.tsx#L573): the initial HTTP canvas fetch can race with websocket init and overwrite fresher live state with an older snapshot.
- `[P2]` [ws.py](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\server\app\ws.py#L202): malformed websocket `canvasId` values are still not validated before the UUID-backed membership query, so bad URLs can fail noisily instead of being rejected cleanly.

Sessions 1 and 2 look clean in this pass. The earlier session-1 auth-envelope and token-shape issues are fixed, and the session-2 invalid-canvas-id bug is fixed as well. The earlier session-3 cross-canvas mutation and type-mutation issues also look fixed, and session 4 is now wired into the app.

Verification:
- `py_compile` passed for [auth.py](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\server\app\auth.py), [canvas.py](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\server\app\canvas.py), and [ws.py](C:\Users\sahil\OneDrive\Documents\GitHub\Mechanize_takehome\server\app\ws.py).
- I did not run a full Docker or frontend build in this pass.

